WEBVTT

00:22.900 --> 00:24.960
CHAPTER XXXVIII.

00:25.540 --> 00:27.440
THE BEND IN THE ROAD.

00:27.440 --> 00:32.900
Marilla went to town the next day and returned in the evening. Anne had gone over to Orchard Slope

00:32.900 --> 00:37.880
with Diana and came back to find Marilla in the kitchen, sitting by the table with her head

00:37.880 --> 00:43.000
leaning on her hand. Something in her dejected attitude struck a chill to Anne's heart.

00:43.600 --> 00:46.840
She had never seen Marilla sit limply inert like that.

00:47.280 --> 00:48.760
Are you very tired, Marilla?

00:49.540 --> 00:54.720
Yes, no, oh, I don't know, said Marilla wearily, looking up.

00:55.340 --> 00:59.880
I suppose I am tired, but I haven't thought about it. It's not that.

01:00.840 --> 01:02.040
Did you see the oculist?

01:02.320 --> 01:04.800
What did he say? asked Anne anxiously.

01:06.040 --> 01:12.580
Yes, I saw him. He examined my eyes. He says that if I give up all reading and sewing entirely,

01:13.420 --> 01:17.760
and any kind of work that strains the eyes, and if I'm careful not to cry,

01:18.360 --> 01:22.860
and if I wear the glasses he's given me, he thinks my eyes may not get any worse,

01:22.860 --> 01:24.760
and my headaches will be cured.

01:25.880 --> 01:29.700
But if I don't, he says I'll certainly be stone blind in six months.

01:30.540 --> 01:33.000
Blind? Anne, just think of it.

01:34.100 --> 01:38.600
For a minute Anne, after her first quick exclamation of dismay, was silent.

01:39.700 --> 01:45.460
It seemed to her that she could not speak. Then she said bravely, but with a catch in her voice.

01:46.680 --> 01:50.280
Marilla, don't think of it. You know he has given you hope.

01:50.280 --> 01:53.400
If you are careful, you won't lose your sight altogether.

01:54.020 --> 01:57.260
And if his glasses cure your headaches, it will be a great thing.

01:58.280 --> 02:01.460
I don't call it much hope, said Marilla bitterly.

02:01.740 --> 02:05.200
What am I to live for if I can't read or sew, or do anything like that?

02:05.560 --> 02:11.480
I might as well be blind, or dead. And as for crying, I can't help that when I get lonesome.

02:11.880 --> 02:16.880
But there, it's no good talking about it. If you'll give me a cup of tea, I'll be thankful.

02:16.880 --> 02:22.340
I'm about done out. Don't say anything about this to anyone for a spell yet, anyway.

02:22.740 --> 02:26.460
I can't bear that folks should come here to question and sympathize and talk about it.

02:27.900 --> 02:31.440
When Marilla had eaten her lunch, Anne persuaded her to go to bed.

02:31.980 --> 02:36.220
Then Anne went herself to the east gable and sat down by her window in the darkness,

02:36.400 --> 02:39.180
alone with her tears and her heaviness of heart.

02:39.980 --> 02:44.100
How sadly things had changed since she had sat there the night after coming home.

02:44.540 --> 02:49.000
Then she had been full of hope and joy and the future had looked rosy with promise.

02:50.160 --> 02:55.240
Anne felt as if she had lived years since then, but before she went to bed there was a smile on

02:55.240 --> 03:00.220
her lips and peace in her heart. She had looked her duty courageously in the face and found it

03:00.220 --> 03:06.460
a friend, as duty ever is when we meet it frankly. One afternoon, a few days later,

03:06.840 --> 03:10.440
Marilla came slowly in from the front yard where she had been talking to a caller,

03:10.440 --> 03:16.760
a man whom Anne knew by sight as Sadler from Carmody. Anne wondered what he could have been

03:16.760 --> 03:21.760
saying to bring that look to Marilla's face. What did Mr. Sadler want, Marilla?

03:22.540 --> 03:26.680
Marilla sat down by the window and looked at Anne. There were tears in her eyes in

03:26.680 --> 03:30.680
defiance of the oculus prohibition and her voice broke as she said,

03:31.900 --> 03:36.040
He heard that I was going to sell Green Gables and he wants to buy it.

03:37.200 --> 03:42.080
Buy it? Buy Green Gables? Anne wondered if she had heard her right.

03:42.860 --> 03:45.640
Oh, Marilla, you don't mean to sell Green Gables.

03:46.780 --> 03:53.700
Anne, I don't know what else is to be done. I've thought it all over. If my eyes were strong,

03:53.800 --> 03:58.180
I could stay here and make out to look after things and manage with a good hired man,

03:58.180 --> 04:05.880
but as it is, I can't. I may lose my sight altogether and anyway I'll not be fit to

04:05.880 --> 04:10.800
run things. Oh, I never thought I'd live to see the day when I'd have to sell my home,

04:11.460 --> 04:15.840
but things would only go behind worse and worse all the time till nobody would want to buy it.

04:16.520 --> 04:21.660
Every cent of our money went in that bank and there's some notes Matthew gave last fall to pay.

04:22.380 --> 04:27.200
Mrs. Lynde advises me to sell the farm and board somewhere, with her I suppose.

04:27.960 --> 04:33.580
It won't bring much. It's small and the buildings are old, but it'll be enough for me to live on,

04:33.580 --> 04:40.240
I reckon. I'm thankful you're provided for with that scholarship, Anne. I'm sorry you won't have

04:40.240 --> 04:45.120
a home to come to in your vacations, that's all, but I suppose you'll manage somehow.

04:46.260 --> 04:48.520
Marilla broke down and wept bitterly.

04:49.940 --> 04:53.620
You mustn't sell Green Gables, said Anne resolutely.

04:55.140 --> 05:01.360
Oh, Anne, I wish I didn't have to, but you can see for yourself. I can't stay here alone.

05:01.740 --> 05:06.820
I'd go crazy with trouble and loneliness, and my sight would go. I know it would.

05:08.600 --> 05:13.920
You won't have to stay here alone, Marilla. I'll be with you. I'm not going to Redmond.

05:16.360 --> 05:21.520
Not going to Redmond? Marilla lifted her worn face from her hands and looked at Anne.

05:22.240 --> 05:23.620
Why, what do you mean?

05:24.780 --> 05:29.980
Just what I say. I'm not going to take the scholarship. I decided so the night after

05:29.980 --> 05:34.800
you came home from town. You surely don't think I could leave you alone in your trouble, Marilla,

05:35.140 --> 05:42.080
after all you've done for me? I've been thinking and planning. Let me tell you my plans. Mr. Barry

05:42.080 --> 05:47.420
wants to rent the farm for next year, so you won't have any bother over that, and I'm going

05:47.420 --> 05:53.220
to teach. I've applied for the school here, but I don't expect to get it, for I understand

05:53.220 --> 05:59.380
the trustees have promised it to Gilbert Blythe, but I can have the Carmody School. Mr. Blair told

05:59.380 --> 06:04.060
me so last night at the store. Of course, that won't be quite as nice or convenient as if I had

06:04.060 --> 06:09.740
the Avonlea School, but I can board home and drive myself over to Carmody and back, in the warm

06:09.740 --> 06:16.380
weather at least, and even in winter I can come home Fridays. We'll keep a horse for that. Oh,

06:16.380 --> 06:22.080
I have it all planned out, Marilla, and I'll read to you and keep you cheered up. You shan't be dull

06:22.080 --> 06:28.860
or lonesome, and we'll be real cosy and happy here together, you and I. Marilla had listened like a

06:28.860 --> 06:35.720
woman in a dream. Oh, Anne, I could get on real well if you were here, I know, but I can't let

06:35.720 --> 06:42.660
you sacrifice yourself so for me. It would be terrible. Nonsense, Anne laughed merrily. There is

06:42.660 --> 06:48.260
no sacrifice. Nothing would be worse than giving up Green Gables. Nothing could hurt me more.

06:48.780 --> 06:54.320
We must keep the dear old place. My mind is quite made up, Marilla. I'm not going to Redmond,

06:54.560 --> 06:58.780
and I am going to stay here and teach. Don't you worry about me a bit.

06:59.780 --> 07:01.580
But your ambitions and...

07:02.780 --> 07:08.760
I'm just as ambitious as ever, only I've changed the object of my ambitions. I'm going to be a good

07:08.760 --> 07:14.780
teacher, and I'm going to save your eyesight. Besides, I mean to study at home here and take a

07:14.780 --> 07:20.300
little college course all by myself. Oh, I've dozens of plans, Marilla, and I've been thinking

07:20.300 --> 07:25.780
them over for a week. I shall give life here my best, and I believe it will give its best to me

07:25.780 --> 07:31.060
in return. When I left Queens, my future seemed to stretch out before me like a straight road.

07:31.540 --> 07:37.680
I thought I could see along it for many a milestone. Now there is a bend in it. I don't

07:37.680 --> 07:43.540
know what lies around the bend, but I'm going to believe that the best does. It has a fascination

07:43.540 --> 07:50.080
of its own, that bend, Marilla. I wonder how the road beyond it goes, what there is of green,

07:50.080 --> 07:55.720
glory and soft checkered light and shadows, what new landscapes, what new beauties,

07:56.060 --> 08:02.420
what curves and hills and valleys further on. I don't feel as if I ought to let you give it up,

08:02.700 --> 08:08.920
said Marilla, referring to the scholarship. But you can't prevent me. I'm sixteen and a half,

08:09.320 --> 08:15.820
obstinate as a mule, as Mrs. Lynde once told me, laughed Anne. Oh, Marilla, don't you go

08:15.820 --> 08:21.820
I don't like to be pitied, and there's no need for it. I'm heart-glad over the very thought

08:21.820 --> 08:27.820
of staying at Dear Green Gables. Nobody could love it as you and I do, so we must keep it.

08:29.340 --> 08:34.080
You blessed girl, said Marilla, yielding, I feel as if you'd given me new life.

08:34.480 --> 08:40.180
I guess I ought to stick out and make you go to college. But I know I can't, so I ain't going to

08:40.180 --> 08:47.140
cry. I'll make it up to you, though, Anne. When it became noised abroad in Avonlea that Anne

08:47.140 --> 08:51.540
Shirley had given up the idea of going to college and intended to stay home and teach,

08:51.800 --> 08:57.420
there was a good deal of discussion over it. Most of the good folks, not knowing about Marilla's

08:57.420 --> 09:04.080
eyes, thought she was foolish. Mrs. Allen did not. She told Anne so in approving words that

09:04.080 --> 09:10.160
brought tears of pleasure to the girl's eyes. Neither did good Mrs. Lynde. She came up

09:10.160 --> 09:14.620
one evening and found Anne and Marilla sitting at the front door in the warm scented summer dusk.

09:14.960 --> 09:19.760
They liked to sit there when the twilight came down and the white moths flew about in the garden

09:19.760 --> 09:26.120
and the odor of mint filled the dewy air. Mrs. Rachel deposited her substantial person upon the

09:26.120 --> 09:30.680
stone bench by the door, behind which grew a row of tall pink and yellow hollyhocks,

09:30.960 --> 09:37.160
with a long breath of mingled weariness and relief. I declare, I'm getting glad to sit down.

09:37.160 --> 09:42.440
I've been on my feet all day, and two hundred pounds is a good bit for two feet to carry around.

09:43.420 --> 09:47.000
It's a good blessing not to be fat, Marilla. I hope you appreciate it.

09:48.020 --> 09:53.740
Well, Anne, I hear you've given up your notion of going to college. I was real glad to hear it.

09:54.000 --> 09:58.980
You've got as much education now as a woman can be comfortable with. I don't believe in

09:58.980 --> 10:03.240
girls going to college with the men and cramming their heads full of Latin and Greek and all that

10:03.240 --> 10:09.760
nonsense. But I'm going to study Latin and Greek just the same, Mrs. Lynde, said Anne, laughing.

10:10.180 --> 10:15.380
I'm going to take my arts courses right here at Green Gables and study everything that I would

10:15.380 --> 10:22.140
at college. Mrs. Lynde lifted her hands in holy horror. Anne, surely you'll kill yourself.

10:23.120 --> 10:31.440
Not a bit of it. I shall thrive on it. Oh, I'm not going to overdo things. As Josiah Allen's wife

10:31.440 --> 10:37.580
says, I shall be medium. But I'll have lots of spare time in the long winter evenings,

10:37.800 --> 10:42.160
and I've no vocation for fancy work. I'm going to teach over at Carmody, you know.

10:42.900 --> 10:46.720
I don't know it. I guess you're going to teach right here in Avonlea.

10:46.860 --> 10:49.120
The trustees have decided to give you the school.

10:50.100 --> 10:54.140
Mrs. Lynde, cried Anne, springing to her feet in her surprise.

10:54.620 --> 10:57.260
Why, I thought they had promised it to Gilbert Blythe.

10:57.840 --> 11:03.160
So they did. But as soon as Gilbert heard that you had applied for it, he went to them—they

11:03.160 --> 11:07.260
had a business meeting at the school last night, you know—and told them that he withdrew his

11:07.260 --> 11:13.040
application and suggested that they accept yours. He said he was going to teach at White Sands.

11:13.420 --> 11:18.520
Of course, he knew how much you wanted to stay with Marilla, and I must say I think it was real

11:18.520 --> 11:24.760
kind and thoughtful in him, that's what. Real self-sacrificing, too, for he'll have his board

11:24.760 --> 11:29.440
pay at White Sands, and everybody knows he's got to earn his own way through college.

11:30.120 --> 11:35.420
So the trustees decided to take you. I was tickled to death when Thomas came home and told me.

11:36.360 --> 11:39.320
I don't feel like I ought to take it, murmured Anne. I mean,

11:39.780 --> 11:43.900
I don't think I ought to let Gilbert make such a sacrifice for—for me.

11:45.060 --> 11:49.700
I guess you can prevent it now. He signed papers with the White Sands trustees,

11:50.160 --> 11:52.940
so it wouldn't do him any good now if you were to refuse.

11:53.340 --> 11:58.740
Of course you'll take the school. You'll get along all right now that there are no pies going.

11:59.180 --> 12:02.900
Josie was the last of them, and a good thing she was, that's what.

12:03.700 --> 12:07.740
There's been some pie or other going to Avonlea School for the last twenty years,

12:07.840 --> 12:12.420
and I guess their mission in life was to keep schoolteachers reminded that earth isn't their

12:12.420 --> 12:18.060
home. Bless my heart! What does all that winking and blinking at the Berry Gable mean?

12:18.840 --> 12:21.760
Diana is signaling for me to go over, laughed Anne.

12:22.440 --> 12:27.040
You know we keep up the old custom. Excuse me while I run over and see what she wants.

12:27.740 --> 12:32.040
Anne ran down the clover slope like a deer and disappeared in the furry shadows of the haunted

12:32.040 --> 12:37.540
wood. Mrs. Lynde looked after her indulgently. There's a good deal of the child about her yet,

12:37.600 --> 12:44.100
in some ways. There's a good deal more of the woman about her in others, retorted Marilla with

12:44.100 --> 12:49.480
momentary return of her old crispness. But crispness was no longer Marilla's distinguishing

12:49.480 --> 12:54.880
characteristic, as Mrs. Lynde told her Thomas that night. Marilla Cuthbert has gotten mellow,

12:55.000 --> 13:00.960
that's what. Anne went to the little Avonlea graveyard the next evening to put fresh flowers

13:00.960 --> 13:07.280
on Matthew's grave and water the Scotch rose bush. She lingered there until dusk, liking the

13:07.280 --> 13:12.900
peace and calm of the little place with its poplars whose rustle was like low friendly speech and its

13:12.900 --> 13:18.540
whispering grasses growing at will among the graves. When she finally left it and walked down

13:18.540 --> 13:24.160
the long hill that sloped to the lake of shining waters, it was past sunset and all Avonlea lay

13:24.160 --> 13:29.840
before her in a dreamlike afterlight, a haunt of ancient peace. There was a freshness in the air

13:29.840 --> 13:35.380
as of a wind that had blown over honey-sweet fields of clover. Home lights twinkled here and there

13:35.380 --> 13:41.260
among the homestead trees. Beyond lay the sea, misty and purple, with its haunting unceasing

13:41.260 --> 13:46.840
murmur. The west was a glowing of soft mingled hues and the pond reflected them all in still

13:46.840 --> 13:52.420
softer shadings. The beauty of it all thrilled Anne's heart and she gratefully opened the gates

13:52.420 --> 13:59.420
of her soul to it. Dear old world, she murmured, you are very lovely and I'm glad to be alive in

13:59.420 --> 14:05.340
you. Halfway down the hill a tall lad came whistling out of a gate before the Blythe homestead.

14:05.340 --> 14:11.980
It was Gilbert and the whistle died on his lips as he recognized Anne. He lifted his cap courteously

14:11.980 --> 14:16.440
but he would have passed on in silence if Anne had not stopped and held out her hand.

14:17.420 --> 14:22.260
Gilbert, she said with scarlet cheeks, I want to thank you for giving up the school for me.

14:22.540 --> 14:27.840
It was very good of you and I want you to know that I appreciate it. Gilbert took her offered

14:27.840 --> 14:33.280
hand eagerly. It wasn't particularly good of me at all, Anne. I was pleased to be able to do you

14:33.280 --> 14:38.160
some small service. Are we going to be friends after this? Have you really forgiven me my old

14:38.160 --> 14:44.220
fault? Anne laughed and tried unsuccessfully to withdraw her hand. I forgave you that day by the

14:44.220 --> 14:50.440
pond landing, although I didn't know it. What a stubborn little goose I was. I've been. I may as

14:50.440 --> 14:56.220
well make a complete confession. I've been sorry ever since. We're going to be the best of friends,

14:56.360 --> 15:01.460
said Gilbert jubilantly. We were born to be good friends, Anne. You've thwarted destiny enough.

15:01.460 --> 15:06.620
I know we can help each other in many ways. You're going to keep up your studies, aren't you?

15:06.820 --> 15:09.660
So am I. Come, I'm going to walk home with you.

15:10.540 --> 15:13.720
Marilla looked curiously at Anne when the latter entered the kitchen.

15:13.920 --> 15:15.980
Who was that that came up the lane with you, Anne?

15:16.460 --> 15:21.360
Gilbert Blythe, answered Anne, vexed to find herself blushing. I met him at Berry's Hill.

15:22.040 --> 15:26.120
I didn't think you and Gilbert Blythe were such good friends that you'd stand for half an hour

15:26.120 --> 15:29.280
the gate talking to him, said Marilla with a dry smile.

15:29.960 --> 15:35.220
We haven't been. We've been good enemies. But we have decided that it will be much more sensible

15:35.220 --> 15:41.020
to be good friends in the future. Were we really there half an hour? It seemed just a few minutes.

15:41.540 --> 15:45.180
But you see, we have five years lost conversations to catch up with, Marilla.

15:46.280 --> 15:49.980
Anne sat long at her window that night, companioned by a glad content.

15:50.820 --> 15:55.040
The wind purred softly in the cherry boughs, and the mint breaths came up to her.

15:55.040 --> 15:58.560
The stars twinkled over the pointed firs in the hollow,

15:59.080 --> 16:01.400
and Diana's light gleamed through the old gap.

16:02.220 --> 16:06.520
Anne's horizons had closed in since the night she had sat there after coming home from Queen's.

16:07.340 --> 16:10.300
But if the path set before her feet was to be narrow,

16:10.540 --> 16:13.720
she knew that flowers of quiet happiness would bloom along it.

16:13.960 --> 16:18.780
The joy of sincere work and worthy aspiration and congenial friendship were to be hers.

16:19.340 --> 16:23.480
Nothing could rob her of her birthright of fancy or her ideal world of dreams.

16:23.480 --> 16:25.980
And there was always the bend in the road.

16:26.680 --> 16:31.540
God's in his heaven. All's right with the world, whispered Anne softly.

